{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509202","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509202"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:14:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:14:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11402"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11402"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.1,0.16,0.11,0.31]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4038"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105568"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4038","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4038"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11402"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87993"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1481"},{"type":"tags","id":"2664"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4630"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5190"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5991"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13083"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37507"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37548"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40121"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42588"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105568","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105568"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset severe chest pain radiating to her back, which began one hour ago while she was at rest. She describes the pain as tearing in nature and rates it as 9 out of 10 in severity. She also reports shortness of breath and has become increasingly light-headed.\u003Cbr\u003E\u003Cbr\u003EShe has a history of hypertension and hypercholesterolaemia. Her regular medications are amlodipine and atorvastatin. She does not smoke or use alcohol.\u003Cbr\u003E\u003Cbr\u003EOn examination, she appears acutely unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure is 90/50 mmHg in the right arm and 120/60 mmHg in the left arm, respiratory rate is 24/min, SpO2 is 97% on room air, and temperature is 36.7\u00b0C. There is no peripheral oedema. Her jugular venous pressure is elevated at 6 cm above the sternal angle. On cardiac auscultation, a new murmur is heard.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the murmur most likely heard on auscultation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ejection systolic murmur at the right second intercostal space","Mid-diastolic murmur with an opening snap at the apex","Pansystolic murmur at the cardiac apex","Holosystolic murmur at the left lower sternal border","Early diastolic murmur at the left third intercostal space"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEarly diastolic murmur at the left third intercostal space\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of aortic regurgitation, which in this scenario is acute and secondary to aortic dissection. The clinical features in the stem\u2014sudden onset severe, tearing chest pain radiating to the back, hypotension, pulse and blood pressure differential between arms, and a new murmur\u2014are classic for aortic dissection. The involvement of the aortic root can cause acute aortic regurgitation, leading to rapid decompensation, pulmonary oedema, and a soft, early diastolic decrescendo murmur best heard at the left sternal border. In acute cases, the classic peripheral signs of chronic aortic regurgitation may be absent due to the rapid haemodynamic compromise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEjection systolic murmur at the right second intercostal space\u003C/strong\u003E is typical of aortic stenosis, which usually presents with exertional syncope, angina, or heart failure, and a crescendo-decrescendo systolic murmur, not with acute tearing chest pain and heart failure as seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMid-diastolic murmur with an opening snap at the apex\u003C/strong\u003E is the classic finding in mitral stenosis, which is associated with chronic symptoms such as exertional dyspnoea and atrial fibrillation, not with acute chest pain or aortic dissection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPansystolic murmur at the cardiac apex\u003C/strong\u003E is typical of mitral regurgitation, which may cause acute pulmonary oedema but is not the expected murmur in aortic dissection with regurgitation. Mitral regurgitation murmurs are best heard at the apex and radiate to the axilla.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHolosystolic murmur at the left lower sternal border\u003C/strong\u003E is typical of tricuspid regurgitation, which is associated with right-sided heart failure and is not linked to aortic dissection or acute aortic regurgitation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAortic dissection should be suspected in any person with sudden, severe, tearing chest pain radiating to the back, especially with pulse or blood pressure differentials between limbs and a new murmur. Acute aortic regurgitation is a life-threatening complication requiring urgent recognition and surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cbr\u003E\u003Cdiv class=\u0022table-container\u0022\u003E\u003Ctable border=\u00221\u0022 cellpadding=\u00224\u0022 cellspacing=\u00220\u0022\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Cth\u003EMurmur\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003ELocation\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003ECharacteristic\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003ESystolic/Diastolic\u003C/th\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EAortic stenosis\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ERight second intercostal space\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ECrescendo-decrescendo, radiates to carotids\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ESystolic\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EAortic regurgitation\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ELeft third intercostal space (left sternal border)\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EEarly diastolic, decrescendo\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EDiastolic\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EMitral stenosis\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EApex\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EMid-diastolic, with opening snap\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EDiastolic\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EMitral regurgitation\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EApex\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EPansystolic, radiates to axilla\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ESystolic\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ETricuspid regurgitation\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ELeft lower sternal border\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EHolosystolic, increases with inspiration\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ESystolic\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003C/table\u003E\u003C/div\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Acute aortic regurgitation can occur as a complication of aortic dissection and presents with sudden onset heart failure.","An early diastolic murmur at the left sternal border is characteristic of aortic regurgitation, including in acute presentations.","Acute aortic regurgitation may not have the classic peripheral signs seen in chronic cases and is a medical emergency."],"references":["National Library of Medicine, StatPearls, Aortic Regurgitation, Nov 2023 \u003Chttps://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK555944/#:~:text=AR%20is%20associated%20with%20widened,and%20over%20the%20carotid%20arteries.\u003E","Aortic aneurysms. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2013 May 28;42:364\u20139. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2013/june/aortic-aneurysms"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87993"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11402"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87993","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/87993"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-10T16:05:30+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-10T16:08:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4038"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105568"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating 